items.abstract: <jats:p>Fracture toughness <jats:italic>K</jats:italic><jats:italic><jats:sub>Ic</jats:sub></jats:italic> and four-point bending strength<jats:italic> σ</jats:italic><jats:italic><jats:sub>c</jats:sub></jats:italic> at high temperature (up to 1500 °C) of Y<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> ceramics of various grain size were measured. The ceramics were prepared by pressureless air sintering and next hot isostatic pressing of high purity (99.99%) Y<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> powder. Relative density of about 99 % was achieved. Photos of microstructures revealed small pores distributed mainly inside grains. For smallest grain size (2 - 9 μm) ceramics <jats:italic>K</jats:italic><jats:italic><jats:sub>Ic</jats:sub></jats:italic> and <jats:italic>σ</jats:italic><jats:italic><jats:sub>c</jats:sub></jats:italic> are almost constant from 20 ° to 1200 °C and next they decrease. For biggest grain size (about 44 μm) they increase up to 800 °C and next they keep constant up to 1200 °C. The micrographs analyses of fracture surfaces indicated that transgranular mode of fracture at room temperature changes to almost intergranular at higher temperatures.</jats:p>
title: Fracture Mechanics of Y<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> Ceramics at High Temperatures

items.abstract:
<jats:p>The aim of the paper is theoretical modelling and experimental verification of the nonsymmetric
thermal shock crack propagation in compound ceramic Al2O3 and ZrO2. The theoretical
problem formulation concerns the thermal shock problem in a strip or bar made of nonhomogeneous
material, which can exhibit local fluctuation of its mechanical and thermal properties.
Such approach allows for: analysis of the real non-homogeneous ceramic materials and solution of
the composition optimisation problem for composite material with respect to thermal shock
sensitivity. In particular the presented approach enables estimation of the stress intensity factors
during thermal shock for any continuous composition of the ceramic material.</jats:p>
title: The Comparative Analysis of the Non-Symmetric Thermal Shock Crack Propagation in Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> and ZrO<sub>2</sub> Bars
